<subSubSection pageId="144" pageNumber="745" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="144" pageNumber="745" startId="144.[1981,2153,296,330]" targetBox="[1366,1957,306,720]" targetPageId="144">
<paragraph blockId="144.[1980,2575,296,724]" pageId="144" pageNumber="745">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1981,2156,296,330]" pageId="144" pageNumber="745">Distribution.</emphasis>
Cuanza River Basin and other rivers draining into AtlanticOcean, NW Angola.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="144" pageNumber="745" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="144.[1980,2575,296,724]" pageId="144" pageNumber="745">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1981,2261,414,448]" pageId="144" pageNumber="745">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 178-184 mm, tail 100-109 mm, ear 22 mm, hindfoot 31-33 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. The Cuanza Vlei Rat is large and robust, with large blunt head and shaggy fur. Fur is brown, mixed with iridescent black above and paler buffy gray below. Tail is short (¢.58% of head-
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="144.[1368,2575,729,1157]" pageId="144" pageNumber="745">body length), black above and paler below, with short bristles. Females have two pairs of nipples. Each upper incisor has single groove, and each lower incisor has one deep and one shallow groove. M, has four laminae, and M” has 6-7 laminae.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1370,2359,848,882]" pageId="144" pageNumber="745" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="144.[1368,2575,729,1157]" box="[1370,2359,848,882]" pageId="144" pageNumber="745">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1370,1481,848,882]" pageId="144" pageNumber="745">Habitat.</emphasis>
Montane grassland and swamps at elevations of 1000-2500 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
